    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Boulders marked with deep, parallel furrows. There is no consensus as to the reason for these grooves, but it is possible that these rocks were used to polish stone tools in prehistoric times, or as timekeeping marks.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000093981/Henriksson, The Grooves on the Island of Gotland in the Baltic Sea (2000)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Rotsblokken gemarkeerd met diepe, parallelle groeven die gevonden worden doorheen heel Europa. Hoewel er geen zekerheid is over de oorzaak van deze groeven, zou het kunnen dat deze stenen gebruikt werden om stenen werktuigen te polijsten.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
